- Dynamic Size Stack :
A dynamic size stack, also known as a resizable stack, is a stack that can grow or shrink in size as needed. 
Dynamic size stacks are implemented using dynamic arrays, such as ArrayLists in Java or LinkedList.
                    - Dynamic size stacks have the following advantages:
                                               - They can grow or shrink in size as needed, making them more flexible than fixed size stacks.
                                               - They do not waste memory because they can resize dynamically.
                                               - They can accept any number of elements, unlike fixed size stacks.
                    - dynamic size stacks also have a few disadvantages:
                                               - They may be slower than fixed size stacks because of the overhead involved in resizing.
                                               - They may cause memory fragmentation if elements are frequently added and removed.
                                               - They may not be as memory-efficient as fixed size stacks for small data sets.










 ********************************************* CODE *****************************************************************

import java.util.Stack;

public class MyStack {

    int stack[];
    int topIndx ;
    int maxCapacity;

   public MyStack(int maxCapacity){
        stack=new int[maxCapacity];
        topIndx=-1;
        this.maxCapacity=maxCapacity;
    }

    public void  push(int element){
       if(topIndx>=maxCapacity-1){
           System.out.println("stack is full -overflow");
           return;
       }
       topIndx++;
       stack[topIndx]=element;
    }

    public boolean isEmpty(){
       if(topIndx<=-1){
           return true;
       }
       return false;
    }

    public int size(){
      return topIndx+1;
    }

    public int peek(){
       if(isEmpty()){
           return Integer.MIN_VALUE;
       }
       return stack[topIndx];
    }

    public int pop(){
       int val = peek();
       if(val!=Integer.MIN_VALUE){
           topIndx--;
       }
       return val;
    }

    public int get(int indx){
       if(topIndx<=-1){
          return Integer.MIN_VALUE;
       }
        return stack[indx];
    }

    public void printStack(){
       for (int i=0; i<=topIndx; i++){
           System.out.print(stack[i]+" ");
       }

    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
     MyStack myStack = new MyStack(5);
     myStack.push(8);
     myStack.push(4);
     myStack.push(9);
     myStack.push(5);
     myStack.push(88);
     
    }
}























